{
  "id": "A1_GF3",
  "level": "A1",
  "type": "grammarFocus",
  "number": "GF3",
  "title": "Trennbare Verben",
  "subtitle": "Separable verbs and their prefix positions",
  "focus": ["Separable Verbs", "Satzklammer", "Past Participle"],
  "conceptSections": [
    {
      "id": "gf3-concept-1",
      "heading": "How separable verbs work",
      "explanation": "Many German verbs have a prefix that separates from the verb stem in main clauses. The conjugated stem stays in position 2, while the prefix moves to the very end of the sentence. This creates a 'bracket' (Satzklammer) around the middle of the sentence. For example: 'ankommen' → 'Ich komme um 8 Uhr an.' — the 'an' goes to the end.",
      "examples": [
        { "de": "ankommen → Ich komme um 8 Uhr an.", "en": "to arrive → I arrive at 8 o'clock.", "note": "an- separates to end" },
        { "de": "aufstehen → Er steht jeden Tag früh auf.", "en": "to get up → He gets up early every day.", "note": "auf- separates to end" },
        { "de": "einkaufen → Wir kaufen am Samstag ein.", "en": "to shop → We shop on Saturday.", "note": "ein- separates to end" }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "gf3-concept-2",
      "heading": "Common separable verbs",
      "explanation": "Here are 12 frequently used separable verbs at A1 level. Learn the complete verb and practise splitting it in sentences.",
      "examples": [
        { "de": "Ich stehe um sechs Uhr auf.", "en": "I get up at six o'clock.", "note": "aufstehen" },
        { "de": "Der Zug kommt pünktlich an.", "en": "The train arrives on time.", "note": "ankommen" },
        { "de": "Sie fängt morgen mit der Arbeit an.", "en": "She starts work tomorrow.", "note": "anfangen" },
        { "de": "Bitte räum dein Zimmer auf!", "en": "Please tidy your room!", "note": "aufräumen" },
        { "de": "Er macht das Licht aus.", "en": "He turns off the light.", "note": "ausmachen" },
        { "de": "Wir laden euch zur Party ein.", "en": "We invite you to the party.", "note": "einladen" },
        { "de": "Sie kauft im Supermarkt ein.", "en": "She shops at the supermarket.", "note": "einkaufen" },
        { "de": "Ich rufe dich heute Abend an.", "en": "I'll call you this evening.", "note": "anrufen" },
        { "de": "Machst du bitte das Fenster auf?", "en": "Would you please open the window?", "note": "aufmachen" },
        { "de": "Der Film fängt um acht an.", "en": "The movie starts at eight.", "note": "anfangen" },
        { "de": "Kommst du mit?", "en": "Are you coming along?", "note": "mitkommen" },
        { "de": "Er gibt das Geld zurück.", "en": "He gives the money back.", "note": "zurückgeben" }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "gf3-concept-3",
      "heading": "Past participle of separable verbs",
      "explanation": "When forming the past participle (Partizip II) of a separable verb, the 'ge-' is inserted between the prefix and the stem. For regular (weak) verbs the ending is '-t', for irregular (strong) verbs it is '-en' with a possible stem change.",
      "table": {
        "headers": ["Infinitive", "Past Participle", "Pattern"],
        "rows": [
          ["einkaufen", "eingekauft", "ein + ge + kauf + t"],
          ["aufräumen", "aufgeräumt", "auf + ge + räum + t"],
          ["anrufen", "angerufen", "an + ge + ruf + en"],
          ["aufstehen", "aufgestanden", "auf + ge + stand + en"],
          ["ankommen", "angekommen", "an + ge + komm + en"],
          ["anfangen", "angefangen", "an + ge + fang + en"],
          ["einladen", "eingeladen", "ein + ge + lad + en"],
          ["mitkommen", "mitgekommen", "mit + ge + komm + en"]
        ]
      },
      "examples": [
        { "de": "Ich habe gestern eingekauft.", "en": "I went shopping yesterday.", "note": "einkaufen → eingekauft" },
        { "de": "Er ist schon angekommen.", "en": "He has already arrived.", "note": "ankommen → angekommen" },
        { "de": "Wir haben das Zimmer aufgeräumt.", "en": "We tidied the room.", "note": "aufräumen → aufgeräumt" }
      ]
    }
  ],
